repnme.cdata!:
Iran - Primary Health Care and Family
            Planning Project

abstracts.cdata!:
Although overall, Iran has achieved a
            remarkable improvement of health outcomes of the population
            since it first established its innovative primary health
            care network in the late 1980s and during the ten-year
            period of project implementation, the project did not
            achieve its specific objectives and the project outcome is
            therefore given an unsatisfactory rating. however, this ICR
            rates overall project sustainability as likely. World Bank
            performance is considered unsatisfactory, although Bank
            management and staff were very responsive in giving good
            quality sector advise and in providing assistance to resolve
            project implementation issues in a timely manner. Borrower
            performance overall was also unsatisfactory despite
            Government cooperation because unfamiliarity with Bank
            policies, guidelines and procedures, and conflicts between
            these conditions and Iranian laws and administrative
            procedures, obstructed senior Government officials to take
            timely actions to expedite project implementation. Lessons
            learned were described broadly as recognizing the need for
            rigorous sector analysis where Bank knowledge of a sector is
            minimal as well as rigorous institutional and capacity
            analysis at all levels of implementation; and being willing
            to invest adequate resources. Some specific lessons focused
            on involving all key partners in project preparation; and
            developing a sound project implementation plan owned by the
            Borrower for each component while building capacity of
            counterpart staff.

repnme.cdata!:
Iran - Primary Health Care and Family
            Planning Project

abstracts.cdata!:
The project seeks to improve the
            delivery of Primary Health Care (PHC) services by
            strengthening the network of Rural Health Centers (RHCs) in
            selected geographic areas. A center for training in the
            management of health and family planning services will be
            established at a national level. RHCs constitute the
            cornerstone of the Iranian health care delivery system in
            rural areas. They provide comprehensive Primary Health Care
            (PHC) services and are essential to the development and
            operation of outreach services. The project will provide the
            necessary civil works, equipment and furniture, transport
            facilities, training and salaries to establish 623 RHCs in
            14 provinces. The project will assist in rapidly expanding
            the Government's family planning program and
            strengthening its institutional base. Services will be
            provided through the primary health care network. The family
            planning component will have four parts: (1) diversifying
            the contraceptive method mix and expanding family planning
            services; (2) building the Ministry's institutional
            capacity at central and provincial levels to plan, manage
            and deliver family planning services; (3) developing
            information-education-communication capabilities to reach
            target groups; and (4) establishing a capacity for program
            evaluation and research in family planning through the use
            of specific studies. The project will examine the fee
            structure, the private sector role in tertiary care, and
            establishing a national medical insurance scheme.
